' Definitions of logaoedic metre are given by Hephaestion and Aristi- des Quintilianus. These, unhappily, are not complete. The reason oi this, however, is apparent: the metre was relatively unimportant. Both authors add their statements about it to their general treatment of the larger subjects of dactylic and anapaestic metres. But the essential fact is made clear. Hephaestion briefly defines logaoedic metre to be the combination, within the same colon, oi two or more dactyls with a trochaic syzygy, or, in ascending rhythm, of two or more anapaests with a catalectic iambic syzygy (bacchius). The most noted form, he adds, in the second category has four anapaests, the first of which may be a spondee or iambus.1 Logaoedic cola, thus defined, are comparatively rare in Greek comedy.²
